{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9e601374-44c4-41b5-9b7a-25cadad44d05","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips for K8s specifically:**\n- If `dotnet tool install` isn't available, use the [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) sidecar instead — it exposes a REST API for trace collection without exec.\n- Copy the trace out with `kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`.\n- If you need **off-CPU** or kernel-level data (e.g., thread pool starvation), use `dotnet-trace collect --profile gc-verbose` or fall back to **`perf`** (requires `SYS_ADMIN` / privileged container).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fe7bed28-dd77-48e1-ba3e-701cae35347f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide concise, practical guidance.","outputTokens":381,"requestId":"5022:D09D:21C8C7:29F323:69F5520E"},"id":"2e4de557-d3f7-4c9d-9505-9973592473e1","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:23:35.297Z","parentId":"4fea1d72-f0e9-4be6-8f1a-f60a90840425"}
